## Potentially Missed Related Work

(These are suggestions, not definitive omissions. The authors may have intentionally excluded them or been unaware of them.)

1. **Toolformer: Language Models Can Teach Themselves to Use Tools** — Schick et al. (2023, arXiv).
   Why potentially missed: Anyprefer's framework centrally relies on external tools (Grounded SAM, Florence-2, BLIP-2, medical imaging models) to assist the judge model in extracting knowledge for response evaluation. Toolformer pioneered the paradigm of tool-augmented language models, demonstrating how LLMs can be enhanced with external tool capabilities through self-supervision. While Anyprefer applies tool integration specifically to preference data synthesis rather than teaching autonomous tool-calling, the foundational methodology of augmenting LLMs with external tools is directly relevant to Anyprefer's judge model design and merits citation in the Related Work section.

